<DocLayout title="Launch Files" activeSection="launch">

  <h1 class="doc-title" id="launch">ROS 2 Launch Files</h1>
  <p class="doc-subtitle">Chapter 9</p>

  <h2 class="section-heading" id="creating-launch-files">9.1 Creating Launch Files</h2>
  <p>Launch files live in the <code>/launch</code> directory of a package. They are used to launch many nodes from within that package all at once. <strong>It is also possible to link launch files from other packages so that multiple nodes from different packages can all be run at once</strong>.</p>
  <p>Your YAML parameter files should thus be located at:</p>

  <CodeBlock code={launchDirCode} lang="bash" customHtml={launchDirCustom} showLegend={true} />

  <p>If there is no <code>launch/</code> directory, create it within ~/.../<code class="ph-generic">[package_name]</code> by using:</p>

  <CodeBlock code="mkdir launch" lang="bash" />

  <p>Enter the <code>/launch</code> directory and create the launch file.</p>
  <p><code class="ph-generic">[extension_type]</code>: <code>.py</code> for Python, <code>.xml</code> for XML or <code>.yaml</code> for YAML.</p>

  <CodeBlock code={touchLaunchCode} lang="bash" customHtml={touchLaunchCustom} showLegend={true} />

  <p>XML and YAML launch files are simplest, but lack the low-level access to general launch features and the scripting abilities of Python launch files.</p>
  <p><strong>NOTE: launch files must have <code>.launch.</code> to be recognized during colcon build.</strong></p>


  <h2 class="section-heading" id="python-launch-files">9.2 Python Launch Files</h2>
  <p>Ensure that you import the proper packages into your Python launch script. <strong>See Section 9.2.4 (Full Structure)</strong> for specifics.</p>

  <h3 class="subsection-heading">9.2.1 Launch Arguments</h3>
  <p>Arguments allow us to pass values at launch time via the command line. They can be used to change which nodes are run, change the values of parameters within those nodes, etc.</p>

  <h4 class="subsection-heading">9.2.1.1 Declaring Arguments</h4>
  <p>You will have to return the variable <code class="ph-var">[return_argument_name]</code> at the end of the launch function.</p>
  <CodeBlock code={pyDeclareArgCode} lang="python" customHtml={pyDeclareArgCustom} showLegend={true} />

  <h4 class="subsection-heading">9.2.1.2 Invoking Arguments</h4>
  <p>Arguments can be invoked within the launch file by using the <code>LaunchConfiguration()</code> function, which can be done in place or by declaring <code class="ph-var">[argument_variable_name]</code> as a reference.</p>
  <CodeBlock code={pyInvokeArgCode} lang="python" customHtml={pyInvokeArgCustom} showLegend={true} />

  <h3 class="subsection-heading">9.2.2 Launching Nodes</h3>
  <p>You will have to return the variable <code class="ph-var">[node_variable_name]</code> at the end of the launch function.</p>
  <CodeBlock code={pyLaunchNodeCode} lang="python" customHtml={pyLaunchNodeCustom} showLegend={true} />

  <p><strong>NOTE: Only package and executable are essential to launching a node, all other aspects are optional</strong>.</p>

  <h4 class="subsection-heading">9.2.2.1 Including Parameter Files</h4>
  <p>Instead of hardcoding parameters within launch scripts, we can simply link a YAML file for these parameters. <strong><code class="ph-generic">[params_package_name]</code> can be different from <code class="ph-generic">[package_name]</code></strong> (you can use parameter files from other packages within your workspace).</p>
  <p>In Python, you must reference the path to the parameters file through a variable and pass it to the parameters block when launching a node.</p>
  <CodeBlock code={pyIncludeParamsCode} lang="python" customHtml={pyIncludeParamsCustom} showLegend={true} />

  <h4 class="subsection-heading">9.2.2.2 Namespaces</h4>
  <p>Namespaces allows you to add the <code>/<span class="ph-generic">[namespace]</span></code> prefix to everything associated with the node being launched: <strong>node names, topics, services, actions, parameters</strong>.</p>
  <CodeBlock code={pyNamespaceCode} lang="python" customHtml={pyNamespaceCustom} showLegend={true} />

  <h4 class="subsection-heading">9.2.2.3 Remapping</h4>
  <p>You can remap the topic or service names used by the node. You must be specific as to which name you would like to remap.</p>
